From Eleanor Reynolds of Magnusson Klemencic Associates. email is attached.

"All,
I know that the test age for this concrete is 56 days, so I am not too worried about the 7-day strength.  However; I went back and reviewed the break data that was submitted for this mix.  Submittal 16 provided test data for CF70BCNT, and the average 7-day strength was 5110psi.   
I am surprised to see that we are consistently getting 7-day breaks around 3500psi when the historic data are so different.  CSI,  why do you think we are seeing such a disparity?"
Eleanor
______________________________

From Eleanor: Email is attached, 

"As we discussed, there is a significant difference between the concrete reaching 9,500psi (only a 5% reduction) or reaching 8,600psi (a 14% reduction).
MKA has reviewed the shear designs, and the walls have enough reserve capacity to accommodate a 5% reduction in final strength, but not a 14% reduction."

The all-thread rod shown in the photo extends down well below what is necessary for the cable hook supports and directly in front of the Hinged Access Door/Panel on the Control Section of the VAV Air Terminal. This is a common issue that repeats on every floor. NFPA 70 2008 (National Electrical Code) Article 110.26(A), (B) identifies the clear distance requirements for Spaces About Electrical Equipment. This requires that all doors and hinged panels to be opened a minimum of 90 degrees . The all-thread rod extending down in front of the Control Section of the VAV Air Terminal prevents compliance with the National Electrical Code and needs to be cut off to allow the hinged panel to be fully opened. I have attached a copy of the referenced code section for your use.

@{"type": "user", "id": "NWKPNYPB9KAR", "name": "John Becker"} 
A ground rod at a lighting pole is an auxiliary grounding electrode (NEC 250.54). Technically they aren't even required, but a good engineering practice to provide a local reference to ground. In the event of a lightning strike, the fault will clear through the ground rod instead of potentially running into the building. All a lighting pole needs per code is an equipment grounding conductor (EGC), which is ran with the lighting circuit.

As far as where the ground rod is located, I have updated the pole base detail in an ASI that will release soon.

The detail #10 on E01-04 is for service entrance grounding, not auxiliary grounding.

NEC 250.8(A) listed all connection methods permitted for grounding and bonding equipment. Included in these are machine screw-type fasteners, thread-forming machine screws, and other listed means. 

-Thomas
